.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have made changes to our own points system to give appropriate priority to peoples’ need to downsize.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have ensured that where we participate in Choice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Based Lettings, for examp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le in North Yorkshire, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the schemes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">give</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> priority to people who need to downsize</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We will not actively prevent people from under-occupying by one bedroom if they have priority for a housing offer. Our policy is to continu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e to allow people to under-occupy as a matter of personal choice because our customers may have few options in meeting their housing requirements due to locality and their personal support networks. </span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As part of the signup process our Neighbourhood teams wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ll offer new customers an affordability check to enable them to make an informed choice when offered a property. We will ask customer to sign an acknowledgement that these assessments have taken place. This will not be a legally binding agreement but an ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ceptance that the Neighbourhood team have carried out the individual assessment based on social housing need.</span></li></ul><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.97pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We continue to facilitate mutual exchanges through Exchange Locata.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If a customer wishes to transfer in order to downsize each case should be deal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t with individually as part of our lettings process and will take account of the housing need and if there are any rent arrears. It is expected that the customer will be able to demonstrate the capacity to repay the arrears in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e future.</span></p><ol start="11" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Neighb</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ourhood sta</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f have </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all received training </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Discretionary Housing Payments to encourage take up where appropriate</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and has recovered £27k direct </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through 196 applications</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Yorkshire Housing is concerned Discretionary Housing Payments </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could be</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> masking the true impact of the welfare reform changes on customers and the business, due to proactively encouraging take up for many of our affected customers</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and is down to the discretion of the Local Authorities. The administration of the scheme is not </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">controlled and varies, Yorkshire Housing have no real measure of the true amount of applications as the payment direct is paid with Housing Benefit </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Moreover local authority liaison meetings have featured conver</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sations regarding anticipated under spend</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Discretionary Housing Payment </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">budget in 2013/14 which </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> returned to</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> G</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment. Yorkshire Housing believes some local authorities </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are being to</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> strict regarding criteria for the fund due to the government guidelines regarding priority groups. This </span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fund needs to be wider reaching to all affe</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cted by welfare reform. The Department of Work and Pensions impact assessments do not identify inequality and social impact. Therefore the discretionary housing payment fund is not protecting some of the most vuln</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erable in society.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. Household Benefit Cap</span><span style="color:#111111; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – Case Studies </span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 11pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Information provided by the Department of Work and Pensions made Yorkshire Housing aware of 33 household benefit cap cases. Yorkshire Housing contacted all households identified to offer support. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From this exercise it was discovered there was a number of cases exempt from the cap due to a member of the household claiming disability benefits or Working Tax Credit.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This proactive approach further supports the need to share information to target servi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ces.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 13.67pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In one local authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, 4 out of 6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cases had social services involvement. Additionally in this local authority, the households were also paying large Council Tax bills due to the local Council Tax Support scheme limited to 70% of liability. Generally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the benefit cap cases consist of large families with several children, therefore they reside in larger homes with a higher council tax banding. This raises questions around whether larger family will b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e able to sustain a tenancy and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Yorkshire Housing has experienced an increase of void</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, specifically three bed and larger properties. We are concerned these families will inevitably re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">turn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> back on our waiting lists or present through our choice based letting schemes, with a high cost to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the business and the tax payer,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">qually so if these customers enter the private sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 16.33pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In a separate case a large family was exempt from the cap due to claiming Working Tax Credit. The working hours of one member have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">been reduced and they are no lon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ger entitled to Working Tax Credit therefore, the cap has been applied. The customer has priority and non-priority debts and is looking to increase their hours; however the concern is this household may fall further into debt, even though they are in work.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 17pt; padding-left:13pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Two cases in one local authority area have had their Housing Benefit award </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reduced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are now</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in receipt of 50p. Currently the penalties are only being deducted from Housing Benefit, in the future, with the introduction of Universal Credit the whole cap </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will be deducted from the entire Universal Credit award, which would be further detrimental to household income. Furthermore there is a lack of clarity on h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ow the ‘switchback’ process will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work. There are a number of concerns such as:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 49.22pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">If a customer is reco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mmended for ‘switchback,’ of rent direct to the landlord, in cases where a penalty has been applied to Housing Benefit and leaves the claimant in receipt of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">50p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, would it be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">50p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> switched back to the landlord? This raises the issue of the cost of administer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ‘switchback’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, specifically in cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a smal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l amount</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of housing benefit remaining.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n addition Yorkshire Housing would still have to pursue the customer to pay their rent.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 49.22pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government has said it will make deductions to other benefits t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o pay back arrears</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pre ‘switchback’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and have said they want to increase the legal amount they can deduct. The result of which will be hardship for some families and could contribute to declining neighbourhoods.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4. Size criteria in the social sector</span></p><ol type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 24pt; text-indent:-24pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sections 130-133 of the Welfare Reform Act 2012 (the 2012 Act) replace</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> data sharing legislation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> new provisions for RSL’s to receive data. These new powers intended to help smooth the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assessment of benefit claims,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> support local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ther ‘qualifying persons’ to carry out functions related to benefits, welfare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> services and council tax.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2012/1483/pdfs/uksi_20121483_en.pdf </span></p><ol start="2" type="i" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 26.67pt; text-indent:-26.67pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From information provided by local authorities </span><span style="font-fa